column1: Will Mick Mulvaney cease to be White House Chief of Staff before 1 January 2020?
column6: ['US Politics']
column11: In December 2018, President Trump announced that Office of Management and Budget Director Mick Mulvaney would replace, in an acting capacity, outgoing Chief of Staff John Kelly (CNN). For the purposes of this question, Mulvaney will be considered the Chief of Staff whether in a permanent or acting capacity (Politico). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

Earlier I took a strong outside view, and neglected the unique circumstances of Mulvaney and the President. I stand by the outside view analysis, but not to the exclusion of entertaining other possibilities. For example: Pres. Trump has reportedly toyed around with the idea of firing Mulvaney. The fact that he hasn't done it yet is evidence that Mulvaney possesses some leverage over the administration. He could be prepared to feed the President to the Democrats in Congress, should he be fired (the rumor mill reports that this is close Mulvaney's own take on the matter). Alternately, he could be being set up as the fall guy for the Ukraine scandal. In either case, the outcome is intimately tied to the Impeachment trial, which is likely to occur (or at least begin) before the end of the year. And, of course, there's a ~40% that this is all completely wrong and I have no idea what's actually going on.

I'm going to be an odd-man-out and continue to keep the chance of dismissal/resignation high. Mick initially tried to split the baby by initiating a judicial review that would determine that he didn't have to appear before committee - contradicting the President's order to simply not appear. Then he tried to join Charles Kupperman's existing suit testing immunity to subpoena, and was rebuffed by that Plaintiff and the judge at a hearing last night. He then indicated to the judge he'd pursue a separate suit. Today his lawyers announce he'll do what he's told to do by the WH, and cease pursuing any suit on the matter, and simply not appear before committee. Cipollone has always wanted Mulvaney off the team, opining that Mulvaney has been at best ineffective, and at worst decidedly counterproductive to the President's interest, and now to his defense. An example of the former was MM's October news conference - Mick has since developed an allergy to podiums. An example of the latter is this attempt at judicial review - had Mulvaney pursued and lost, this would have established the matter into law. Further WH resistance to subpoena would be patently illegal - thus adding a possible Article for obstruction should the WH continue to resist subpoenas. Without a judicial determination - the matter remains in the domain of speculation, and is consistent with the WH effort to run out the clock on the country's interest. Near term - things are such that rather than scapegoating him out the door - Trump will keep him close - in the WH. And yet - I feel there's something behind this now-aborted legal maneuvering that infers that Mick is aware of dire consequences for himself. If true - he may have to decide his best bet to save himself is to resign, and to "come in" and sing.

(CNN)Acting White House chief of staff Mick Mulvaney is on shaky ground in the wake of a bad week for President Trump, according to multiple sources with knowledge of discussions surrounding the whistleblower fallout. The sources say the President is not upset with Mulvaney for the White House releasing the summary of his July 25 call with Ukraine's leader or the whistleblower complaint because he had been convinced that it was necessary. What Trump and other aides are frustrated with, according to the sources, is that Mulvaney did not have a strategy for defending and explaining the contents of those documents as soon as they were publicly released.
